hundreds of times a day. It’s almost as if he has dropped all pretense of governing and is just sitting in front of his television with his smartphone all day long. See CNN, “Trump goes on wild tweetstorm to distract from Fauci testimony.” Among his wild claims on twitter,

Trump is alleging that Obama engaged in “one of the worst crimes in history”—known as Obamagate—that no one can explain, not even Trump. See HuffPo, “Trump Rails About ‘Obamagate,’ But Won’t Explain What It Is At Press Briefing.” In other sordid tweets, Trump claimed that

“Asian Americans” are angry at China over the coronavirus, and implied that television personality Joe Scarborough was responsible for the death of an intern who died because of an undiagnosed heart condition. See Vox, “Trump’s Twitter meltdown is on its third day and has

escalated to baseless murder allegations.” (“The president just baselessly suggested that MSNBC host Joe Scarborough killed an intern. Really.”) In medical terminology, Trump is “off the rails.” He is falling into a twitter black hole so powerful that no coherent thought can

escape. Even his own followers have no idea what he is talking about much of the time—or why. See David Frum in The Atlantic, “Trump Has Lost the Plot.” (“The president is talking about things most Americans can’t comprehend, let alone care about.”) As Frum explains, The more

Trump talks about his crackpot theories, the more he reveals why he plunged the country into such a catastrophe. He never cared about anybody else. He ignored unwelcome realities, because only fantasy flattered his ego as it required to be flattered. . . . But the most important

thing to notice about the Trump-Fox blizzard of mania is how remote it is from anything that real-world voters care about. Trump is losing his grip because his deficiencies have been laid bare by the pandemic, because his nemesis criticized his handling of the government

response, because he knows that the Supreme Court will compel him to turn over his taxes in response to at least one subpoena, and because he is falling in the polls. It is an ugly thing to watch, and it will become uglier as life gets worse for Trump. He has met his match;
